Avoid Introductions and Conclusions: Do not waste time writing formal introductions or conclusions. The mark scheme focuses entirely on scientific content and synoptic links.
Ensure Breadth: Cover at least 4 to 6 distinct sub-topics. Do not group closely related areas in the same section (e.g., covering both xylem and phloem counts as only one topic, as they are in the same section of the specification).
Balance Year 1 and Year 2: Aim to include concepts from both Year 1 (Topics 1-4) and Year 2 (Topics 5-8) of the AQA course.
Prioritize Accuracy: High-scoring essays contain zero significant scientific errors. Stick to topics you know thoroughly rather than writing superficial points you are unsure of

